uploads/2018/08/BLDC.pdf\">BLDC</a>\n\nDriver wiring\n\n<img class=\" wp-image-439 aligncenter\" src=\"https://ecocatamaran.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Picture2-2-520x400.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"569\" height=\"438\">\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','20kW Motor for Boat','','inherit','closed','closed','','403-revision-v1','','','2018-12-18 13:09:33','2018-12-18 13:09:33','',403,'https://ecocatamaran.com/2018/12/18/403-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(484,1,'2018-12-18 13:10:22','2018-12-18 13:10:22','<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-397\" src=\"https://ecocatamaran.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/solar_update3-1-711x400.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"994\" height=\"559\">\n\nLink solar panels :&nbsp;<a href=\"https://irex.vn/san-pham/mono-360-w/\">https://irex.vn/san-pham/mono-360-w/</a>\n\nLink for Charge control :&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.victronenergy.com/upload/documents/Datasheet-SmartSolar-charge-controller-MPPT-250-60,-250-70,-250-85-&amp;-250-100-EN.pdf\">https://www.victronenergy.com/upload/documents/Datasheet-SmartSolar-charge-controller-MPPT-250-60,-250-70,-250-85-&amp;-250-100-EN.pdf</a>\n\nLink for Battery cell :&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.alibaba.com/product-detail/Hot-Items-AWT-60A-26650-3800mah_60212651873.html?spm=a2700.7724838.2017115.23.6b231f70zcJ3zf\">https://www.alibaba.com/product-detail/Hot-Items-AWT-60A-26650-3800mah_60212651873.html?spm=a2700.7724838.2017115.23.6b231f70zcJ3zf</a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nThis is&nbsp;solarwave 64 with 42 solar panels. let see how this going !\n\n- We have 42 solar panel in the boat (3x13 panels )\n<table style=\"height: 130px;\" width=\"957\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"118\">panels</td>\n<td width=\"168\">power(kW) at 25*C</td>\n<td width=\"172\">power(kW) at 40*C</td>\n<td width=\"125\">volt(V)</td>\n<td width=\"128\">current(A)</td>\n<td width=\"110\">area(m2)</td>\n<td width=\"102\">cost(usd)</td>\n<td width=\"217\">Capacity/day at 40* (W.h)</td>\n<td width=\"130\">Weight(Kg)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"118\">42</td>\n<td width=\"168\">15120</td>\n<td width=\"172\">14160.636</td>\n<td width=\"125\">38.55</td>\n<td width=\"128\">392.28</td>\n<td width=\"110\">81.33048</td>\n<td width=\"102\">4998</td>\n<td width=\"217\">92044.134</td>\n<td width=\"130\">924</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n- So, one day we have a total capacity about 92-98 Kw.h need to be saved.\n\n<img class=\"wp-image-399 aligncenter\" src=\"https://ecocatamaran.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Picture7-447x400.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"682\" height=\"610\">\n\n-so the motor we should choose is 48 Volt or 144 Volt system.\n\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-400 aligncenter\" src=\"https://ecocatamaran.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Picture8.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"184\" height=\"147\">\n\n-For 35Kw.h pakage at 48V we need 14 cells = 14*3.7= 51.8V DC\n\n-1 cell have capacity is : 35kW.h / 14 cells=2.5kW.h per cells\n\n-So 1 cell will have 2.5kW.h / (3.7V x 3.8Ah) =178 batteries\n\n-so one battery bank 35kW.h 48 volt have 178 x 14 = 2492 batteries\n\n- We need 3 of them. so, total we need 2492 x3 =7479 batteries\n\n- Let try again total capacity we have : 7479 batteries x 3.7V per battery x 3.8A.h per battery = 105154.74 W.h =105,1 kW.h\n\n-now we try to make 1 cell with 178 batteries. Lets take 180 batteries will be better\n\n180 =2x2x5x3x3\n\nLet talk 12x15 =180 batteries or 12x16-12 =180 batteries.\n\n<strong>When buying a Solar Power system, it pays to understand the different types of technology on offer. There is a lot of marketing hype surrounding the various panel types – and their benefits, so it pays to know what features really matter, and what is just marketing hype before you go shopping!</strong>\n\n<img class=\"wp-image-389 aligncenter\" src=\"https://ecocatamaran.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Picture1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"449\" height=\"262\">\n<table style=\"border-collapse: separate;\" border=\"1\" width=\"739\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" width=\"206\"></td>\n<td width=\"166\">Monocrystalline</td>\n<td width=\"174\">Polycrystalline</td>\n<td width=\"193\">Thin film</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>efficieny</td>\n<td>good (typically 15-20%)</td>\n<td>medium(typically 13-16%)</td>\n<td>bad(typically 7-13%)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>small footprint/output power</td>\n<td>best</td>\n<td>medium</td>\n<td>too bad (twice the roof space)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>working on high temperatures</td>\n<td>bad</td>\n<td>medium</td>\n<td>best</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>costs</td>\n<td>bad ( highest cost)</td>\n<td>medium</td>\n<td>cheepest</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>shade tolerance</td>\n<td>medium</td>\n<td>medium</td>\n<td>best</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>durable</td>\n<td>longest live</td>\n<td>medium</td>\n<td>medium</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\nThere are four common panel types on the market today, they are:\n<ul>\n 	<li>Monocrystalline panels</li>\n 	<li>Polycrystalline panels</li>\n 	<li>Thin film (amorphous silicon) panels</li>\n 	<li>Hybrid panels (which are monocrystalline with an embedded layer of thin film)</li>\n</ul>\n<b>1.Monocrystalline</b><b> silicon solar cells</b>\n\nMonocrystalline silicon solar cells Monocrystalline panels get their name from the fact that the silicon wafer used to make them is cut from a single crystal or ‘boule’ of silicon. Silicon is grown in a laboratory to achieve a high degree of purity and is then sliced very thinly to make wafers.\n\nBenefits :\n<ul>\n 	<li>Monocrystalline cells have the highest efficiency of any cells on the market under standard operating conditions.(typically 15-20%)</li>\n 	<li>Their high efficiency means they have the smallest footprint for their output, so you can maximize power output when roof space is limited.</li>\n 	<li>Monocrystalline solar panels live the longest.</li>\n</ul>\nDrawbacks :\n<ul>\n 	<li>Due to higher production costs, monocrystalline cells are more expensive than other cells.</li>\n 	<li>Monocrystalline cells don’t perform as well as polycrystalline cells or thin film under higher temperatures (e.g. 25°C +). All cells are subject to ‘de-rating’ as the ambient temperature increases, and monocrystalline cells tend to produce less at higher temperatures than the other technologies.</li>\n 	<li>If the solar panel is partially covered with shade, dirt or snow, the entire circuit can break down</li>\n</ul>\n<b>2.Polycrystalline</b><b> silicon cells</b>\n\nThese cells are cut from an ingot of melted and recrystallised silicon. In the manufacturing process, molten silicon is cast into ingots of polycrystalline silicon, then saw-cut into very thin wafers and assembled into complete cells. Polycrystalline cells (also known as multicrystalline) are cheaper to produce than monocrystalline ones, due to the simpler manufacturing process. However, they tend to be slightly less efficient for the same size cell.\n\nBenefits:\n<ul>\n 	<li>Polycrystalline cells typically offer a lower cost per watt of power produced. • These cells have a better temperature de-rating co-efficient compared to monocrystalline, meaning they produce more power in hotter weather, which usually more than offsets their slightly lower cell efficiency.</li>\n</ul>\nDrawbacks:\n<ul>\n 	<li>Polycrystalline cells are slightly less efficient than monocrystalline cells, so they need more roof space to produce the same output capacity. (typically 13-16%)</li>\n</ul>\n<b>3.Thin</b><b> film silicon</b>\n\nThin film, or amorphous, silicon cells are made up of silicon atoms in a thin layer rather than a crystal structure. Amorphous silicon can absorb light more readily than crystalline silicon, so the cells can be thinner. For this reason, amorphous silicon is also known as ‘thin film’ photovoltaic (PV) technology.\n\nBenefits:\n<ul>\n 	<li>Thin film offers the best shade tolerance of any solar technology.</li>\n 	<li>When compared with other types of panels, thin film performs best under hotter temperatures.</li>\n</ul>\nDrawbacks:\n<ul>\n 	<li>Thin film has the lowest conversion efficiency of all the panel types (7–13%)</li>\n 	<li>These panels need about twice the roof space to achieve the same power output as a similar crystalline panel.</li>\n</ul>\n<b>4. Summary:</b>\n<table style=\"height: 360px;\" width=\"1012\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"324\"></td>\n<td width=\"262\"><b>Monocrystalline</b></td>\n<td width=\"273\"><b>Polycrystalline</b></td>\n<td width=\"303\"><b>Thin film</b></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"324\"><b>Efficieny</b></td>\n<td width=\"262\"><strong>good (typically 15-20%)</strong></td>\n<td width=\"273\">medium(typically 13-16%)</td>\n<td width=\"303\">bad(typically 7-13%)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"324\"><b>small footprint/output power</b></td>\n<td width=\"262\"><strong>best</strong></td>\n<td width=\"273\">medium</td>\n<td width=\"303\">too bad (twice the roof space)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"324\"><b>working on high temperatures</b></td>\n<td width=\"262\">bad</td>\n<td width=\"273\">medium</td>\n<td width=\"303\"><strong>best</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"324\"><b>costs</b></td>\n<td width=\"262\">bad ( highest cost)</td>\n<td width=\"273\">medium</td>\n<td width=\"303\"><strong>cheepest</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"324\"><b>shade tolerance</b></td>\n<td width=\"262\">medium</td>\n<td width=\"273\">medium</td>\n<td width=\"303\"><strong>Best</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"324\"><b>durable</b></td>\n<td width=\"262\"><strong>longest live</strong></td>\n<td width=\"273\">medium</td>\n<td width=\"303\">medium</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n&nbsp;\n\nSo, for the high application like a boat we can <b>bypass </b>thin film panel, and with the small size roof we should put the monocrystalline.\nFor the tropical depression with high temperatures as Viet Nam, the monocrystalline panel will be decreased efficiency, but the decreased is trivial. (-0.48 to -0.5% per degree ).with 40 °C we loss about (40°C - 25°C)*0.5%=7.5%. Or Maybe need cooler system.\n\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QuDcZ_nKRlk\n\n<b>2.MPPT</b><b> and </b><b>PWM</b><b> controller</b>\n\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-420 aligncenter\" src=\"https://ecocatamaran.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Picture1-648x400.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"648\" height=\"400\">\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">The I-V curve and P-V curve of solar panel</p>\n\n<ul>\n 	<li>The PWM controller is in essence a switch that connects a solar array to a battery. The result is that the voltage of the array will be pulled down to near that of the battery.</li>\n 	<li>The MPPT controller is more sophisticated (and more expensive): it will adjust its input voltage to harvest the maximum power from the solar array and then transform this power to supply the varying voltage requirement, of the battery plus load. Thus, it essentially decouples the array and battery voltages so that there can be, for example, a 12 volt battery on one side of the MPPT charge controller and a large number of cells wired in series to produce 36 volts on the other.</li>\n</ul>\nPWM:\n\nLet’s assume that you try to combine a low cost PWM Solar inverter with a 24V battery bank and 250W Solar panel. During the charging process the 250w panel will be connected directly to the 24V battery. The ouput current of the panel is 8.28A &nbsp;but with the PWM charging at 24V, this panel will produce only 8.28A X 24V that is 198W (you lost 52Watt).\n\n&nbsp;\n\nMPPT:\n\nIt is possible to connect standard inexpensive grid-tied solar panels to any of our solar battery chargers and inverters. If the Vmp of the solar module is greater (let’s assume 36V for a 250w&nbsp;<a href=\"https://voltaconsolar.com/solar-products/solar-panel.html\">monocrystalline panel</a>) than the battery voltage, then the battery current (Amps) will be adjusted proportionally to be greater than the solar panel input current. &nbsp;The MPPT algorithm can reach 99% efficiency, that means the input and output power will be perfectly balances. MPPT chargers will run your off-grid solar system at the maximum power point , as a result the wast of energy will be negligible.\n\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-421 aligncenter\" src=\"https://ecocatamaran.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Picture2-1-800x292.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"800\" height=\"292\">\n\nYou can imagine that MPPT have 2 period:\n<h3>1.Identify Pmax and take the power with Imppt and Vmppt of the solar panel</h3>\n<h3>2. Convert that power to charge with compatible volt and current of the battery</h3>\n<h3>Video :PWM vs. MPPT Charge Controllers</h3>\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wmyuxKmlBCk\n<h2>recommend for Charge controllers.</h2>\nfor the solar Charge controllers we recommend should be the Victronenergy charge\n\n<img class=\"wp-image-423 aligncenter\" src=\"https://ecocatamaran.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Untitled-1-447x400.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"719\" height=\"643\">\n\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-426 \" src=\"https://ecocatamaran.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/specificationcharge-1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1057\" height=\"1497\">\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','100kW Solar system for the boat','','inherit','closed','closed','','385-revision-v1','','','2018-12-18 13:10:22','2018-12-18 13:10:22','',385,'https://ecocatamaran.com/2018/12/18/385-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(499,5,'2018-12-28 05:19:09','2018-12-28 05:19:09','','Configuring MSK SBASE V1','','inherit','open','closed','','configuring-msk-sbase-v1','','','2018-12-28 05:19:09','2018-12-28 05:19:09','',0,'https://ecocatamaran.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Configuring-MSK-SBASE-V1.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(500,5,'2018-12-28 05:53:08','2018-12-28 05:53:08','<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[501,502]} -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-2 is-cropped\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://i0.wp.com/ecocatamaran.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/MSK-SBASE-V1.2-Wiring.png?fit=850%2C800&amp;ssl=1\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"501\" data-link=\"https://ecocatamaran.com/?attachment_id=501#main\" class=\"wp-image-501\"/></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://i0.wp.com/ecocatamaran.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/MSK-SBASE-V1.2-Wiring-1.png?fit=850%2C800&amp;ssl=1\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"502\" data-link=\"https://ecocatamaran.com/?attachment_id=502#main\" class=\"wp-image-502\"/></figure></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Step1:</strong> Download\nSmoothie firmware <a href=\"https://github.com/Smoothieware/Smoothieware/tree/edge/FirmwareBin\">here</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Step2 :</strong> Download\nfile config <a href=\"http://smoothieware.org/configuring-smoothie\">here</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Step3:</strong> Copy file <em>firmware.bin</em> and <em>config.txt</em> &nbsp;&nbsp;to SD Card.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Step4:</strong> Download\nSmoothie driver for Window&nbsp; <a href=\"http://smoothieware.org/windows-drivers\">here</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Step5</strong>: Connet\nboard with Computer then open config.txt file to adjust parameter.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Configuring\nParameters:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can see list of\nmost configuration options currently understood by the Smoothie firmware <a href=\"http://smoothieware.org/configuration-options\">here</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[504]} -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-1 is-cropped\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://ecocatamaran.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/2.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"504\" data-link=\"https://ecocatamaran.com/?attachment_id=504#main\" class=\"wp-image-504\"/></figure></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<p style=\"text-align:center\">The first change value steps_per_mm to match\nwith your machine. To understand this value you can see <a href=\"http://smoothieware.org/3D-printer-guide#stepper-motors\">here</a> .</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[505]} -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-1 is-cropped\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://ecocatamaran.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/3.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"505\" data-link=\"https://ecocatamaran.com/?attachment_id=505#main\" class=\"wp-image-505\"/></figure></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<p style=\"text-align:center\">\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nChange\ntype temperature sensor if you not use thermistor sensor.\n\n\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The problem that we have had :</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1.Our machine using 24V DC resistor for Hotend so We seen </strong><em><strong>the hotend temperature is rising too fast  and over value setup</strong></em><strong> about 10 degree celcious. It  is stable after about 4 minutes.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong><em>Resolve:&nbsp; </em></strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Open config.txt, find out <em># PID configuration</em> uncommented lines\nbelow: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[506]} -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-1 is-cropped\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://ecocatamaran.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/4.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"506\" data-link=\"https://ecocatamaran.com/?attachment_id=506#main\" class=\"wp-image-506\"/></figure></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Download Pronterface to connect with board <a href=\"http://www.pronterface.com/\">here</a> .</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>                Open Pronterface connect with machines.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n\n Running PID autotune by command : M303 E0 S190\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>             </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong><em>E<strong>0</strong></em></strong><em>&nbsp;is the number of the heater or bed\ntemperature control module, determined by the order that they appear in the\nconfig file. Here it&nbsp; would be 0 for the\nhotend, and 1 for the bed.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>S<strong>190</strong>&nbsp;is\nthe temperature to autotune for. Use the temperature you will be using your\nheater at in real life. For a hotend here we use 190c</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Waiting few minutes then PID\nAutotune compete. Copy&nbsp; new value PID\nreplace your configuration in <em>config.txt</em> </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Reset board, The problem is solved !</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. Two Ac Servo of Z axis is wrong work ( it work with more noise and not same beetwen two motor)  when connect with Smoothie Board (MSK SBASE V1.2) </strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here is Step pulse defaut: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[507],\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-gallery aligncenter columns-1 is-cropped\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://ecocatamaran.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/5.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"507\" data-link=\"https://ecocatamaran.com/?attachment_id=507#main\" class=\"wp-image-507\"/></figure></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<p style=\"text-align:center\">Step pulse MSK\nSBASE V1.2 </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Prolem here is duty cycle of pulse is too small.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Resolve: </strong>Copy contend in box below put it on your  file config, Edit microseconds_per_step_pulse by 5. Restart machine.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><p><em># Stepper module configuration</em></p><p><em>microseconds_per_step_pulse                  5                # Duration of step pulses to stepper drivers, in microseconds / defaut is 1 </em></p><p><em>#minimum_steps_per_minute                     1200             # Never step slower than this  </em></p><p><em>base_stepping_frequency                      200000           # Base frequency for stepping, higher gives smoother movement </em></p></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:gallery {\"ids\":[508]} -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-1 is-cropped\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img src=\"https://ecocatamaran.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/6.png\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"508\" data-link=\"https://ecocatamaran.com/?attachment_id=508#main\" class=\"wp-image-508\"/></figure></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:gallery -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<p style=\"text-align:center\">Step Pulse after\nedit duty cycle</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Configuring MSK SBASE V1.2 Controller with external AC servo Drivers  and 24V DC resistor.','','publish','open','open','','configuring-msk-sbase-v1-2-controller-with-external-ac-servo-drivers-and-24v-dc-resistor','','','2018-12-28 05:53:15','2018-12-28 05:53:15','',0,'https://ecocatamaran.com/?p=500',0,'post','',0),(501,5,'2018-12-28 05:23:59','2018-12-28 05:23:59','','MSK SBASE V1.2 Wiring','','inherit','open','closed','','msk-sbase-v1-2-wiring','','','2018-12-28 05:23:59','2018-12-28 05:23:59','',500,'https://ecocatamaran.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/MSK-SBASE-V1.2-Wiring.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(502,5,'2018-12-28 05:24:21','2018-12-28 05:24:21','','MSK SBASE V1.2 Wiring','','inherit','open','closed','','msk-sbase-v1-2-wiring-2','','','2018-12-28 05:24:21','2018-12-28 05:24:21